Rating: 4
I can't believe I'm saying this but I think we have discovered a new tradition: this will definitely replace pumpkin pie on the family menu from now on!! I made some modifications, with wild success: no crystallized ginger in the crumb/crust for fear of the kids' reaction, but I added a 1/4 tsp of powdered ginger to oomph the flavor. I could have added a bit more. I also really like intense pumpkin/spice flavors; nothing wimpy. So I used the seasonally available pumpkin spice cream cheese from the supermarket, I doubled all the spice measurements and I increased the amount of pumpkin itself to about 1.5 times stated in the recipe. Also: I try to cut back sugar amts wherever I can so I experimented with 1 cup brown sugar and 1 cup Splenda as another recipe alteration. Result: huge luscious deeply pumpkin cheesecake that everyone kept digging into for days; even the kids requested it! We hate marshmallows in the family but I gritted my teeth and actually tried the topping exactly as directed by the recipe and it was a perfect topping for the spiced-up cheesecake; didn't taste marshmallow-y at all... just had a lovely not-overly-sweet creamy texture. I'm glad the other reviews warned about baking time. This cheesecake filled up a deep 10" springform pan and took only 40 minutes to bake... outer edges began slightly cracking at 30 minutes. Watch the baking time carefully and remove when center becomes just slightly ready! It was perfect. Next time I will also reduce crust baking time by a minute or two. I yanked it out after 4 minutes or so when I noticed it beginning to get too brown.

Rating: 4
I wrap the bottom of the springform pan with tin foil, then place the whole thing in a shallow pan of water. Helps immensely with the cracking, and I think color consistency. Don't even bother to cut the cake from the pan, when you cool it, it pulls away from the pan itself. I didn't make the topping, it's a great combination of flavors, not too sweet, without it.

Rating: 4
