Rating: 3
This cheesecake made an elegant substitute for pumpkin pie. I agree with the review to increase the spices slightly. I would also suggest making the topping, as it tempered the very sweet cake. I used the crystallized ginger in the crust and received several compliments, althought I don't know if I would use it again, perhaps just the gingersnaps and pecans. I made a bit more crust than called for and put it into muffin tins into which I poured the batter that didn't fit into my pan (I used a 10-inch and still had leftover batter). It made 7 generous-sized mini cheesecakes that cooked in about 20 minutes. I noticed that the cake was set and only giggly in the center 3" after 1 hour. It turned out very creamy and I definitely think the time called for would have resulted in an overcooked cake. Overall a delicious cake that I will definitely be making for Thanksgiving.

Rating: 2
Unlike many of the reviewers, I didn't have an overflow of filling - it was just the perfect amount. I did find however, that the filling was sort of bland and not pumpkin-spicy enough. So I added more cinnamon, nutmeg and cloves. I agree that the marshmallow topping doesn't really have much flavor, but it was well received by my taste testers. The end result cracked big time, which isn't desirable in a cheesecake. I turned the oven off much earlier than the recipe suggested and let the cheesecake rest, and it was creamy and not overdone. But I think it might have been dry if I let it bake per the recommended instructions. I might make this recipe again, but I'll have to make adjustments. On second thought, because of that, I might just look for another option...life is too short.

Rating: 3
I made two of these a few days ago. I took one with me on a visit to my high school where they devoured it and I left one at home. I can not stop eating it. However, I did make some changes that I felt were necessary. Maybe not to you, but. First, I used a basic graham cracker crust because I've never had gingersnaps and I don't like ginger. But I do like graham cracker crusts. I used a ten-inch springform pan because that's what I have. The batter came almost to the top of the pan. I decreased the amount of sugar to 1 1/3 cups and used firmly packed brown sugar instead of white. I also used two cups of fresh roasted pumpkin instead of canned. The second cheesecake I used butternut squash because I was no longer able to locate some fresh pumpkins. It still tastes like pumpkin to me. I decreased the vanilla to 1 tablespoon because I didn't want to use so much vanilla for a pumpkin cheesecake. Then, I left out the water-bath. Instead, I placed a pan filled about two-thirds with boiling water on the rack beneath the cheesecake. Also, I baked it for twenty minutes at 350ºF, then I lowered the oven to 250ºF and baked it for another hour and a half. Then I left off the marshmallow topping and just served each slice with a drizzle of homemade dulce de leche.

Rating: 0
I don't even like cheesecake, and I couldn't stop eating this. Unlike the other reviewers, I liked the marshmallow topping, and I would suggest making it. I had only about 8 oz of leftover filling, and I used someone else's suggestion of putting it in little souffle cups, which worked nicely. Make sure to use enough cookie crumbs-I don't think that my butter-to-crumb ratio was quite right, and my crust came out really hard. Also--don'e be afraid of the ginger. I don't like ginger, and I thought that it worked nicely in this recipe. I can't say that this will be replacing pumpkin pie at Thanksgiving, but it's a nice seasonally appropriate dessert for those nights where pumpkin sounds nice, but pumpkin pie is not quite right. I definitely think that I'll be making this again.

